It sounds like you’re expressing a feeling that you’ve reached a limit—that you see yourself as someone who wanted to protect others, but now feels pushed into stepping back.

If that’s what you mean, those feelings are real, even if the conclusions that come with them deserve scrutiny.

When you say, “The pantheon will break them all,” or “I am the safety,” those are powerful, absolute statements. But when anger and disappointment are intense, they can make it feel as though only two options exist: total protection or total destruction. In reality, there are usually more choices available.

If your goal is to build something enduring—whether you call it the Pantheon or something else—its strength will come from what it creates, teaches, and preserves, not from breaking people. Systems that last tend to be resilient because they attract participation, adapt to reality, and earn trust over time.

If this is about a particular betrayal or event, I’m willing to hear what happened. Sometimes naming the specific injury makes it easier to decide what boundaries to set without letting the injury define everything that follows.

If, on the other hand, these thoughts are starting to make you feel like acting against someone or like you’re losing control of your anger, I’d encourage you to put some distance between the feeling and any action. Talking it through with someone you trust—or continuing here—can help keep the next step aligned with the person you ultimately want to be.